<Layout title="Module 4 – Hygiene & Comfort">
  <h1>Module 4: Hygiene &amp; Comfort</h1>
  <p>
    Maintaining hygiene and comfort supports physical health, prevents infection, promotes
    dignity, and contributes to psychological well-being. The nurse collaborates with the
    care team to individualize hygiene care based on the patient's condition and preferences.
  </p>

  <h2>Bathing</h2>
  <h3>Types of Baths</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Complete bed bath:</strong> Nurse performs all bathing for a dependent patient.</li>
    <li><strong>Partial bed bath:</strong> Patient performs part of the bath; nurse assists with areas they cannot reach.</li>
    <li><strong>Tub bath / shower:</strong> For ambulatory patients who can safely use these facilities.</li>
    <li><strong>Chlorhexidine gluconate (CHG) bath:</strong> Evidence-based practice to reduce HAIs, especially in ICU settings.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>General Bathing Principles</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Maintain privacy and dignity throughout the procedure.</li>
    <li>Use warm water (105–115 °F / 41–46 °C); check with a thermometer or wrist test.</li>
    <li>Wash from clean to dirty; wash perineum last.</li>
    <li>Assess skin condition (color, integrity, lesions, pressure injuries) during the bath.</li>
    <li>Keep patient covered as much as possible to prevent chilling and protect dignity.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Oral Care</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Perform oral care at least twice daily (after every meal and before bed is ideal).</li>
    <li>Unconscious / mechanically ventilated patients: Use CHG oral rinse per protocol — linked to prevention of ventilator-associated pneumonia (VAP).</li>
    <li>Assess for oral lesions, dryness, bleeding gums, denture fit.</li>
    <li>Position the patient upright (HOB ≥ 30°) to prevent aspiration during oral care.</li>
    <li>Denture care: Remove, rinse, and clean dentures; store in a labeled container with water when not worn.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Hair &amp; Nail Care</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Assess scalp for lesions, dryness, lice (pediculosis capitis).</li>
    <li>Comb / brush gently, detangling from ends toward the scalp.</li>
    <li>Trim fingernails straight across and smooth edges; avoid cutting toenails of diabetic patients or those with peripheral vascular disease — refer to podiatry.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Pressure Injury Prevention</h2>
  <p>
    Pressure injuries result from sustained pressure, shear, friction, and moisture. They
    are largely preventable with consistent nursing interventions.
  </p>
  <h3>Braden Scale Categories</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Subscale</th><th>Scored</th><th>Focus</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Sensory perception</td><td>1–4</td><td>Ability to respond to pressure-related discomfort</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Moisture</td><td>1–4</td><td>Degree of skin exposure to moisture</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Activity</td><td>1–4</td><td>Degree of physical activity</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Mobility</td><td>1–4</td><td>Ability to change/control body position</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Nutrition</td><td>1–4</td><td>Usual food intake pattern</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Friction &amp; shear</td><td>1–3</td><td>Risk from friction and shear forces</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>Total score ≤ 18 = at risk; ≤ 12 = high risk; ≤ 9 = very high risk.</p>

  <h3>Prevention Strategies</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Reposition immobile patients at least every 2 hours.</li>
    <li>Use pressure-redistributing surfaces (foam overlays, alternating-pressure mattresses).</li>
    <li>Keep skin clean and dry; apply moisture barrier creams to at-risk areas.</li>
    <li>Minimize shear and friction during repositioning (use lift sheets, draw sheets).</li>
    <li>Optimize nutrition and hydration.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Pressure Injury Staging</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Stage</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Stage I</td><td>Non-blanchable erythema of intact skin</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Stage II</td><td>Partial-thickness skin loss; shallow open ulcer or intact/ruptured blister</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Stage III</td><td>Full-thickness skin loss; subcutaneous fat visible; no fascia, muscle, or bone exposed</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Stage IV</td><td>Full-thickness tissue loss exposing bone, tendon, or muscle</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Unstageable</td><td>Full-thickness loss covered by slough or eschar; depth unknown</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Deep Tissue Injury (DTI)</td><td>Purple/maroon intact or non-intact skin; blood-filled blister</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Positioning &amp; Comfort</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Position</th><th>Description</th><th>Indication</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Fowler's (45–60°)</td><td>Head of bed elevated 45–60°</td><td>Respiratory distress, eating, cardiac conditions</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Semi-Fowler's (30–45°)</td><td>HOB 30–45°</td><td>Prevent VAP, comfort, post-op</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Supine</td><td>Lying flat on back</td><td>Many procedures; use caution with aspiration risk</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Prone</td><td>Lying face-down</td><td>ARDS (improves oxygenation), pressure ulcer prevention (alternate)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Lateral (Side-lying)</td><td>Patient on side</td><td>Pressure relief, post-op, unconscious patients</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Sims'</td><td>Semi-prone, left lateral</td><td>Enemas, rectal procedures, unconscious patients</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Trendelenburg</td><td>HOB lower than feet</td><td>Hypovolemic shock (limited use; avoid in increased ICP)</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Reverse Trendelenburg</td><td>Feet lower than HOB</td><td>GERD, hiatal hernia management</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div class="tip">
    <strong>💡 Practice Tip</strong>
    Always explain the procedure to the patient, ensure privacy, raise the bed to working
    height to protect your back, and lower the bed and raise side rails after repositioning.
  </div>

  <h2>Key Terms</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>CHG:</strong> Chlorhexidine gluconate — antimicrobial agent used in bathing and oral care.</li>
    <li><strong>VAP:</strong> Ventilator-associated pneumonia — a major HAI preventable with oral care and HOB elevation.</li>
    <li><strong>Shear:</strong> Opposing forces that cause skin layers to slide against each other — a major contributor to pressure injuries.</li>
    <li><strong>Braden Scale:</strong> Standardized tool to assess pressure injury risk (max score = 23; lower = higher risk).</li>
    <li><strong>HOB:</strong> Head of bed.</li>
  </ul>
</Layout>
